rgency Aid before and after 1970 Ambivalences and Contradictions -- tChapter 12 Defining ‘the Third Way’ Oppositional Internationalisms of Finnish, Swedish and West German Student and New Left Movements in the 1960s -- tChapter 13 ‘The Vision of an Undivided, Habitable World’ International Climate Policies in German, British and European Parliamentary Debates on Conceptions of Justice, 1992–2019 -- tChapter 14 Dynamics of the International and National in Finnish and Hungarian Higher Education, 1990–2020 -- tConclusion: Long-Term Patterns in the Vocabulary of Internationalisms -- tAfterword -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is commonplace that the modern world is more international than at any point in human history. Yet the sheer profusion of terms for describing politics beyond the nation state—including “international,” “European,” “global,” “transnational” and “cosmopolitan,” among others – is but one indication of how conceptually complex this field actually is. Taking a wide view of internationalism(s) in Europe since the eighteenth century, Nationalism and Internationalism Intertwined explores discourses and practices to challenge nation-centered histories and trace the entanglements that arise from international cooperation. A multidisciplinary group of scholars in history, discourse studies and digital humanities asks how internationalism has been experienced, understood, constructed, debated and redefined across different European political cultures as well as related to the wider world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aInternationalismxHistory. 0aNation-statexHistory. 0aNationalismzEuropexHistory. 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh  aHistory: 20th Century to Present, History: 18th/19th Century.1 aAndr